  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The titles Ms., Mrs., and Miss are used to address women, but they convey different meanings regarding marital status:\n\n1. **Ms.**: This is a neutral title that can be used regardless of a woman's marital status. It is appropriate when you do not know whether a woman is married or when she prefers not to disclose her marital status. It is commonly used in professional settings and is considered respectful.\n\n   - **Example**: Ms. Smith\n\n2. **Mrs.**: This title is traditionally used for married women. It indicates that the woman has taken her husband\u2019s last name or has chosen to be addressed in this manner. \n\n   - **Example**: Mrs. Johnson (typically means she is married to Mr. Johnson)\n\n3. **Miss**: This title is used for unmarried women, often young women or girls. It conveys that the woman has not yet married.\n\n   - **Example**: Miss Johnson (typically implies she is unmarried)\n\nIn practice, if you are unsure which title to use, \"Ms.\" is usually the safest choice, as it avoids assumptions about marital status. When addressing someone formally, always attempt to use the title they prefer when you know it.",
